Description: CVE-2026-32740 - Fix integer overflow when computing chroma sizes
 Prevents integer overflow in chroma_width() and chroma_height() when
 computing chroma plane dimensions for large image sizes. The expression
 (w+1)/2 can overflow for uint32_t values near UINT32_MAX, leading to
 a heap-buffer-overflow write during grid tile compositing.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/strukturag/libheif/commit/6721f307ad684804b735e917dde7d372c5faae31
Author: Dirk Farin <dirk.farin@gmail.com>
Last-Update: 2026-05-25

--- a/libheif/pixelimage.cc
+++ b/libheif/pixelimage.cc
@@ -54,7 +54,7 @@
   switch (chroma) {
     case heif_chroma_420:
     case heif_chroma_422:
-      return (w+1)/2;
+      return w/2 + (w & 1); // note: prevents integer overflow
     default:
       return w;
   }
@@ -64,7 +64,7 @@
 {
   switch (chroma) {
     case heif_chroma_420:
-      return (h+1)/2;
+      return h/2 + (h & 1); // note: prevents integer overflow
     default:
       return h;
   }
Description: CVE-2026-32882 - Fix overlay image with alpha channels using wrong stride
 The alpha channel pixel offset was computed using in_stride (the color
 channel stride) instead of alpha_stride. When the alpha channel has a
 different stride than the color channel, this causes an out-of-bounds
 read leading to potential information disclosure or crash.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/strukturag/libheif/commit/22b6266bf03a9f016f84a9b57b80e1dd7c79d64a
Author: Dirk Farin <dirk.farin@gmail.com>
Last-Update: 2026-03-15

--- a/libheif/pixelimage.cc
+++ b/libheif/pixelimage.cc
@@ -1328,7 +1328,7 @@
         for (uint32_t x = in_x0; x < in_w; x++) {
           uint8_t* outptr = &out_p[out_x0 + (out_y0 + y - in_y0) * out_stride + x];
           uint8_t in_val = in_p[in_x0 + y * in_stride + x];
-          uint8_t alpha_val = alpha_p[in_x0 + y * in_stride + x];
+          uint8_t alpha_val = alpha_p[in_x0 + y * alpha_stride + x];

           *outptr = (uint8_t) ((in_val * alpha_val + *outptr * (255 - alpha_val)) / 255);
         }
Description: Fix possible buffer overflow when reading mask image
 When reading a mask image, the memcpy used data.size() as the copy length
 which could exceed the allocated buffer. This fixes it by using the actual
 image dimensions (width * height) and corrects the stride comparison cast.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/strukturag/libheif/commit/123694271ac02f2de68a3ccdc5d483eb8a2ae593
Author: Dirk Farin <dirk.farin@gmail.com>
Last-Update: 2026-03-05

--- a/libheif/image-items/mask_image.cc
+++ b/libheif/image-items/mask_image.cc
@@ -113,8 +113,8 @@

   size_t stride;
   uint8_t* dst = img->get_plane(heif_channel_Y, &stride);
-  if (((uint32_t)stride) == width) {
-    memcpy(dst, data.data(), data.size());
+  if (stride == static_cast<size_t>(width)) {
+    memcpy(dst, data.data(), static_cast<size_t>(width) * height);
   }
